    <bioghist id="aspace_31b8bc98c1278da48a8b01fdd95e061b">
      <head>Biographical/Historical note</head>
      <p>John Auer, pharmacologist at the Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research from 1907 to 1921. Worked in the laboratory of his father-in-law, S.J. Meltzer.</p>
      <p>Dr. Auer's association with The Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research began with grant support for a three year period at $500 a year on researches with Dr. Prudden. When he joined the Institute he worked in the laboratory of S.J. Meltzer who was his father-in-law. His investigations were on: Digestion, respiration and heart. They also, studied the anaphylactic caused functional disturbances; physiological action of various drugs and many studies on war gas, tetanus, reflexes and connective tissue.</p>
      <chronlist>
        <head>Biographical note</head>
        <chronitem>
          <date>1875</date>
          <eventgrp>
            <event>Born March 30, Rochester, New York</event>
          </eventgrp>
        </chronitem>
        <chronitem>
          <date>1898</date>
          <eventgrp>
            <event>S.B. University of Michigan</event>
          </eventgrp>
        </chronitem>
        <chronitem>
          <date>1902</date>
          <eventgrp>
            <event>M.D. Johns Hopkins Medical School</event>
          </eventgrp>
        </chronitem>
        <chronitem>
          <date>1903</date>
          <eventgrp>
            <event>Married October 1 to Clara Meltzer of NYC Children: James, Helen, John</event>
          </eventgrp>
        </chronitem>
        <chronitem>
          <date>1902-1903</date>
          <eventgrp>
            <event>Medical House Officer, Johns Hopkins Hospital, Baltimore, Md.</event>
          </eventgrp>
        </chronitem>
        <chronitem>
          <date>1903-1905</date>
          <eventgrp>
            <event>Three year grant from RIMR through T.M. Prudden $500 for each year; Letter head at the address of 22 Mount Morris Park West, NYC suggests he and his wife Clara Meltzer Auer carried on the private practice of medicine at this period.</event>
          </eventgrp>
        </chronitem>
        <chronitem>
          <date>1906-1907</date>
          <eventgrp>
            <event>Instructor in physiology, Harvard Medical School</event>
          </eventgrp>
        </chronitem>
        <chronitem>
          <date>1906-1907</date>
          <eventgrp>
            <event>Resident Fellow, Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research</event>
          </eventgrp>
        </chronitem>
        <chronitem>
          <date>1907-1908</date>
          <eventgrp>
            <event>Assistant in Physiology, RIMR</event>
          </eventgrp>
        </chronitem>
        <chronitem>
          <date>1908-1909</date>
          <eventgrp>
            <event>Associate in Physiology, RIMR</event>
          </eventgrp>
        </chronitem>
        <chronitem>
          <date>1909-1921</date>
          <eventgrp>
            <event>Associate Member in Physiology and Pharmacology, RIMR</event>
          </eventgrp>
        </chronitem>
        <chronitem>
          <date>1921-</date>
          <eventgrp>
            <event>Professor of Pharmacology and Director of the department St. Louis University School of Medicine</event>
          </eventgrp>
        </chronitem>
        <chronitem>
          <date>1924-</date>
          <eventgrp>
            <event>Also Pharmacologist St. Mary's Group of Hospitals, St. Louis</event>
          </eventgrp>
        </chronitem>
        <chronitem>
          <date>1948</date>
          <eventgrp>
            <event>Died April 30</event>
          </eventgrp>
        </chronitem>
      </chronlist>
      <p>Member of: American Physiological Society, American Society of Pharmacology and Experimental Therapeutics; Secretary 1912-1916; President 1924-1927, Society for Experimental Biology and Medicine; Vice-President 1917-1919, Association of American Physicians, Harvey Society, St. Louis Academy of Sciences, St. Louis Medical Society, Maj. M.O.R.C. 1917-1922</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent id="aspace_f5863857ee1d8ab3dfee99aa2d5f94f6">
